skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:3:description: Design and generate custom Rhei state machine YAML files from project specifications and team structures. Use when users need a workflow that doesn't fit the default rhei state machine — domain-specific phases, multi-team handoffs, approval gates, counted review loops, model-specific states, or automated callback integrations.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:8:Design a custom Rhei state machine only when the built-in `rhei` workflow is too generic. Produce a YAML file that matches the project's real phases, actors, gates, retries, and automation hooks, ready to be referenced by a plan's `**States:**` declaration.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:22:- Transition callbacks or conditional routing
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:54:- States that must not advance autonomously
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:56:- Model-specific execution, if different models own different states
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:62:Emit one YAML file that conforms to the current Rhei state-machine format. The file has five sections: `name`/`version`, optional `models`, `states`, `transitions`, `profiles`, `node_policy`, and optional `callbacks` / `error_handling`.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:64:When this skill is used from `rhei-template-writer`, emit template-ready YAML for `<template>/states.yaml`: include the full machine, preserve any needed `{{...}}` instantiation variables, and add the template-required ASCII diagram comment block before `name:`. Do not return only a transition sketch or prose description.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:72:- `states`
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:89:- `instructions` — strongly recommended for every non-terminal state
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:90:- `final: true` on terminal states
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:92:> `initial: true` is **not** a state-level field. Initial states are declared on each profile under the top-level `profiles` block; `node_policy` routes each node to a profile.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:96:- `gating: true` for states that require explicit human action to exit
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:102:- `agent:` — overrides the agent id assigned by `rhei next` in this state
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:104:### Transition fields
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:128:Every machine declares at least one profile. A profile defines the *policy* applied to a node: where it starts and which states it may ever hold.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:142:- Every profile must declare `initial` and a non-empty `allowed` list.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:177:states:
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:182:    instructions: |
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:186:      are resolved by `rhei next` before output.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:204:    description: <when and why this transition occurs>
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:235:`inputs:` and `outputs:` turn files into first-class transition prerequisites. They are part of execution semantics, not markdown syntax:
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:237:- `rhei next` will refuse to claim a task if any `inputs:` file for the current state is missing, and prints an explicit missing-artifact error.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:238:- `rhei transition` and `rhei complete` will refuse to leave a state if any `outputs:` file has not been written.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:242:Use artifact contracts in preference to prose like "write your review to foo.md and transition" — the runtime enforces them structurally and `instructions` can reference them via `{input.<name>.path}` / `{output.<name>.path}`.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:246:### States
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:249:2. Name states after the phase, not the team. Prefer `security-review` over `security-team`.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:250:3. Do **not** set `initial: true` on any state. Initial states live on profiles.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:252:5. Mark human gates explicitly with `gating: true`, and also say in `instructions` that the state must not transition out autonomously. `rhei next` will refuse to claim tasks in gating states; `rhei complete` will refuse to exit them.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:253:6. Keep the machine proportional to the workflow. If it grows past roughly 15 states, consider splitting workflows.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:254:7. Use `visits` only when the workflow intentionally loops through the same state and should eventually escalate or take another exit. Visit 1 renders as the unsuffixed name; later visits render as `<name>-<n>` in markdown.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:258:1. Declare every legal transition explicitly. Unlisted transitions are forbidden — this is the core safety property.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:260:3. Multiple outgoing transitions represent distinct outcomes; document each in `description`. Under `rhei run` orchestrator authority, use `condition` / `exit_code` to route among them rather than relying on `instructions` prose.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:264:7. Do not define outgoing transitions from final states.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:265:8. Avoid prose-only gates for machine-critical decisions. If a decision changes what the machine is allowed to do, encode it as a gating state, artifact contract, transition condition, exit-code route, or callback result that the runtime can observe.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:277:1. Write instructions for the actor in that state.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:278:2. Describe the domain work only. Under `rhei run` orchestrator authority, exit conditions are encoded structurally — via `outputs:` artifacts and transition `condition` / `exit_code` — not in prose. Gating states are the exception: their instructions address a human reader and should explicitly say "do not transition out of this state autonomously."
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:280:4. For gating states, say who decides and what decision they are making.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:283:### Automation, queues, and publish states
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:285:1. **Define idempotency for recurring sweeps.** If a state or callback repeatedly scans for work, say what durable marker, artifact, external id, or de-duplication key prevents reprocessing the same item on the next run.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:287:3. **Make publish states re-check review outputs before acting.** A state that releases, publishes, merges, deploys, or notifies externally must consume the review/approval artifacts as `inputs:` and verify the latest result is still affirmative immediately before performing the side effect.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:288:4. **Give publish states a negative path.** If the required review artifact is missing, stale, rejected, or internally inconsistent, the machine should route to review, blocked, cancelled, or failed instead of publishing.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:289:5. **Keep external side effects idempotent.** Publish and callback states should be safe to retry after a crash or interrupted `rhei run`; use external ids, lock files, status artifacts, or read-before-write checks where appropriate.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:295:3. List the real phases, gates, retries, handoffs, and per-state artifacts.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:296:4. Draft state names, descriptions, and instructions.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:301:9. Write the YAML file to `docs/states.yaml` or `docs/states/<name>.yaml` (or the `.agents/rhei/` paths — see *File Placement*).
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:302:10. Validate the result with the CLI when available.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:304:If authoring for a Rhei Template, write the YAML to `<template>/states.yaml` instead and ensure the template's plan skeleton declares the same machine name with `**States:** <name>`.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:313:- Every transition has `from`, `to`, and `description`.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:314:- Gating states are marked with `gating: true` and their instructions forbid autonomous exit.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:315:- Machine-critical decisions are represented by gating states, artifacts, conditions, exit-code routes, or callback results; they are not present only as prose instructions.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:320:- Recurring sweep states or callbacks define an idempotency strategy and a durable marker or de-duplication rule.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:322:- Publish, merge, deploy, release, and notify states re-check the latest review or approval artifacts through `inputs:` before acting and have a non-publish path for missing, stale, or negative review results.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:323:- State names are lowercase hyphenated identifiers (matching the `IDENTIFIER` grammar production). States whose names contain spaces or punctuation are legal but must be referenced in markdown via backticks.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:331:- No orphan states (defined in `states` but not referenced by any profile's `allowed`, transition, or override).
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:336:rhei states --state-machine <path>
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:341:For template-authored machines that still contain `{{...}}` instantiation placeholders, do not validate the raw `<template>/states.yaml` directly. Instantiate the template first, then validate the rendered workspace's state machine.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:347:- `docs/states.yaml` — single machine for the project, auto-discovered by a sibling or workspace-root plan.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:348:- `docs/states/<name>.yaml` — multiple machines in the project.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:349:- `.agents/rhei/states.yaml` / `.agents/rhei/states/<name>.yaml` — for projects that keep agent configuration under `.agents/`.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:351:Plans normally pick up a sibling or workspace-root `states.yaml` automatically when they declare `**States:** <name>`. The YAML file's `name` must match the declaration. Use `--state-machine <path>` when overriding the conventional auto-discovered file.
